<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="172" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,1844,2013]" lastBlockId="21.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="172" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">
<taxonomicName box="[199,527,1879,1904]" class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Africorchestia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrispinosa">
<emphasis box="[199,527,1879,1904]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Africorchestia quadrispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was first described by K.H. Barnard in 1916, but has been less studied than 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Capeorchestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">C. capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and little is known about its ecology. It is found on kelp-dominated sandy shores on the 
<collectingRegion box="[1281,1404,1917,1940]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">West coast</collectingRegion>
of Southern Africa (
<figureCitation box="[346,423,1952,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[345,1241,1154,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[340,1247,1150,1905]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 13. Map of South Africa (RSA) and Namibia (NAM) showing the geographical distribution of Capeorchestia capensis (solid line), Africorchestia quadrispinosa (dotted line) and A. meridionalis (dashed line). The spatial distribution of C. capensis overlap with the one of A. quadrispinosa (on the west coast of South Africa) and with A. meridionalis (south coast of South Africa)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272051/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Fig 13</figureCitation>
), from 
<collectingRegion box="[507,565,1952,1976]" country="South Africa" name="Western Cape" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Cape</collectingRegion>
Aghulas (
<collectingRegion box="[680,841,1952,1976]" country="South Africa" name="Western Cape" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Western Cape</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[853,999,1952,1977]" name="South Africa" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">South Africa</collectingCountry>
) to the Skeleton 
<collectingRegion box="[1191,1255,1952,1976]" country="New Zealand" name="West Coast" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Coast</collectingRegion>
Park (
<collectingCountry box="[1329,1429,1952,1977]" name="Namibia" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Namibia</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Branch" box="[158,371,1988,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" refString="Branch, G. M., Griffiths, C. L., Branch, M. L. &amp; Beckley, L. F. (2008) Two Oceans: A guide to the marine life of southern Africa. Struik Publishers, Cape Town / Johannesburg, 368 pp." type="book" year="2008">
Branch 
<emphasis box="[248,304,1988,2013]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Baldanzi" box="[382,613,1988,2013]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" refString="Baldanzi, S., McQuaid, C. D., Cannicci, S. &amp; Porri, F. (2013) Environmental Domains and Range-Limiting Mechanisms: Testing the Abundant Centre Hypothesis Using Southern African Sandhoppers. PLoS ONE, 8, e 54598. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0054598" type="journal article" year="2013">
Baldanzi 
<emphasis box="[489,545,1988,2013]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). The abundance of 
<taxonomicName box="[840,1031,1988,2013]" class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Africorchestia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrispinosa">
<emphasis box="[840,1031,1988,2013]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">A. quadrispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is higher towards the northern limit of distribution (Namibian coasts), while animals are bigger in size towards the southern limit (
<bibRefCitation author="Baldanzi" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" refString="Baldanzi, S., McQuaid, C. D., Cannicci, S. &amp; Porri, F. (2013) Environmental Domains and Range-Limiting Mechanisms: Testing the Abundant Centre Hypothesis Using Southern African Sandhoppers. PLoS ONE, 8, e 54598. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0054598" type="journal article" year="2013">
Baldanzi 
<emphasis box="[1369,1429,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">et al.</emphasis>
, 2013
</bibRefCitation>
). The previous authors, during the collection survey in winter 2010, found no differences in size between males and females and absence of ovigerous females, suggesting a different reproductive cycle than 
<emphasis box="[1298,1436,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">
<taxonomicName box="[1298,1431,224,248]" class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Capeorchestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capensis">C. capensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
collected during the same period of time (SB pers. obs). The abundance of 
<taxonomicName box="[1013,1206,260,285]" class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Africorchestia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrispinosa">
<emphasis box="[1013,1206,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">A. quadrispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was well correlated with salinity, sand temperature, debris coverage and morphodynamic state of the shore (
<bibRefCitation author="Baldanzi" box="[1147,1382,295,320]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" refString="Baldanzi, S., McQuaid, C. D., Cannicci, S. &amp; Porri, F. (2013) Environmental Domains and Range-Limiting Mechanisms: Testing the Abundant Centre Hypothesis Using Southern African Sandhoppers. PLoS ONE, 8, e 54598. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0054598" type="journal article" year="2013">
Baldanzi 
<emphasis box="[1256,1314,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). No data are available on behavioural and feeding ecology of 
<taxonomicName box="[831,1026,332,357]" class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Africorchestia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrispinosa">
<emphasis box="[831,1026,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">A. quadrispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, observations during the surveys in 2010, 
<date box="[344,513,367,392]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" value="2011" valueMax="2012">2011 and 2012</date>
, lead to consider 
<taxonomicName box="[711,902,367,392]" class="Malacostraca" family="Talitridae" genus="Africorchestia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrispinosa">
<emphasis box="[711,902,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">A. quadrispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a sand-hopper (
<emphasis box="[1116,1178,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">sensu</emphasis>
Bousfield, 1992), as it burrows deep in the sand when necessary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
